    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that's a good start. but what about the different ways people tried to get things done? like, was there really just one way it worked, or did people disagree on how to handle things?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The civil rights movement was marked by a diversity of tactics, with some advocating for nonviolent civil disobedience, like Martin Luther King Jr.'s approach, while others, like Malcolm X and the Black Panther Party, employed more militant methods, including armed self-defense and community empowerment. The Student Nonviolent Coordinating Committee (SNCC) and the Southern Christian Leadership Conference (SCLC) were more focused on nonviolent direct action, whereas the Black Panther Party and the Nation of Islam focused on community-based programs and self-reliance. These differing approaches often led to conflicts and disagreements within the movement, but ultimately, the nonviolent approach proved more effective in achieving mainstream acceptance and policy change.",
